🐻 Practice, practice, practice!
🐻 If you spend any time out on bear country and carry bear spray on you, it’s so important that you take some time to practice retrieving the spray and getting ready to use it in a hurry. 
🐻 It might surprise you how clumsy you can be at first, but keep practicing and your reaction time and technique will improve! 
🐻It’s also important that you practice with the different holders you use. Maybe you use a belt on some occasions and the side of your backpack on others. Practice them all!
🐻Also carefully practice actually removing the safety on the spray (which I purposely did not do in this reel).
🐻 Only practice it outdoors!
🐻Get practicing and please share this reminder reel with anyone else you know that spends time out in bear country!

🐻 When you buy a new bear spray it comes with a plastic zip tie for safe shipping. Don't forget to remove this prior to taking it out on an adventure!
🐻Not sure if it's time to pick up a new bear spray yet? You need to pick up a new canister if: 
✔️yours is expired
✔️if you can no longer see an expiration date on your canister
✔️if the canister has been used or been damaged in any way
✔️if you've had your bear spray out in extreme cold temperatures this past winter (as cold temps can decrease the pressure within the can).
🐻Be wild wise and happy adventuring!

Do you have a bear call? What is it? Here is mine! 
🐻 People tend to fall into their personal bear call, and I'm not too sure where mine came from. But if you happen to be on the same trail as me, you will hear me coming! 
🐻Making human noise is the most effective way to avoid a bear encounter. If a bear knows you are coming, they will likely leave the area, and your chances of having an encounter (especially a defensive bear encounter)decreases. Usually defensive encounters/attacks are a result of surprising a bear (which makes you appear as a threat to them), and it's hard to surprise it when it hears you coming!
🐻AKA be noisy while out on the land in bear country 😉

Is the Yukon's Tombstone Territorial Park on your bucket list yet? 

🏔️ I recently got back from another dreamy five day hike on one of my favourite trails here in the Yukon in Tombstone Territorial Park. This park is truly a hikers and backcountry campers paradise with so many options for day and multi day adventures.

🥾 I keep coming back to hike in this park because the rugged tundra landscape and jagged mountains are truly some of the most stunning views I've ever seen! 👀 

⛺️ The 46km hike I just did is quite physically challenging (which I love) and you are so remote from everything in one of the most fragile landscapes in Canada (more pikas than people because Yukon Parks limits the number of visitors in their more popular  backcountry camping sites).

❄️From summer blizzards, steep scree slopes, never ending boulder fields and lots of wildlife company, this park has a way of making you appreciate that hot cup of coffee and to understand the meaning of Type 2 Fun. ☕️

✨ 2023 recap of my favourite moments and experiences.✨2023 was a roller coaster with so many mental health challenges but also some of the best memories I'll ever have. Here is a little insight into those moments 👇🏼👇🏼

📸 1: Spending another 5 days in the backcountry of one of my favourite places with someone who was experiencing it for the first time.

📸2: Planning a group hike over Instagram and ending up with life long friends. 

📸3: Being part of my friends journey to becoming an overnight hiker.

📸4: Standing with a melting glacier.
